 <body>
  <root>
   <title>
    Semantical considerations on multiagent only knowing.
   </title>
   <content>
    <section label="1">
     <section-title>
      Introduction
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      When considering knowledge-based agents, it seems natural to think that the beliefs of the agent are precisely those that follow from the assumption that the knowledge base (KB) is all that is known.{sup:1} Think, for example, of an agent whose KB has a secret p, and nothing else. The agent, then, should not only infer that she knows a secret, which is p, but also that she does not know of any other secrets. In some situations it may be possible to fully specify the beliefs and non-beliefs of an agent, in which case classical epistemic logic suffices [1]. But in general, as has been argued elsewhere [2], [3], a perspicuous characterization of the agent's epistemic state is very useful. This is especially significant from the perspective of a designer of some putative agent who would be representing the agent's beliefs in terms of a KB.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Levesque [4] was among the first to capture such a notion explicitly in his logic of “only knowing.” His proposal, the logic {a mathematical formula}OL, is very simple. He augments a logic of belief [5], [6], where (say) the modality K denotes knowledge, with a modality O to capture the notion of only knowing. Beliefs are reasoned about in terms of valid sentences of the form:{a mathematical formula} which is to be read as “if KB is all that is believed by the agent, then the agent knows α.” What is particularly interesting about the new modality is that it not only allows one to draw conclusions about what is known but also about what is not. For example, {a mathematical formula}Op⊃¬Kq and, by introspection, {a mathematical formula}Op⊃K¬Kq both come out valid. Note that this is quite different from classical epistemic logic, in the sense that if we replace O by K, then neither of these sentences is valid. Thus, an agent is able to reason about its own ignorance, without having to be told explicitly what it does not know. Remarkably, the new modality has very intuitive (and simple) truth conditions: roughly a semantics is specified wrt a set of worlds e, where worlds are truth valuations; a KB is only known just in case it is true in all worlds in e and one cannot add more worlds without falsifying at least one of the formulas of the KB. These ideas have since been applied to a number of knowledge representation problems, including, for example, reasoning about dynamical systems [7].
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      When the KB itself refers to an agent's beliefs, then only knowing also exhibits a form of nonmonotonic reasoning. For example, consider the infamous Tweety default formulated as the following sentence δ:{a mathematical formula} which says that birds fly unless believed otherwise. Then, {a mathematical formula}O(Bird(Tweety)∧δ)⊃KFly(Tweety) is a valid sentence in Levesque's logic, and so Tweety is formally off the ground (as desired).
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Readers may note that the nonmonotonicity exhibited by only knowing feels similar in spirit to Moore's autoepistemic logic (AEL) [8]. Levesque substantiated this by proving that Moore's stable expansions of a KB α, which are defined meta-theoretically using fixpoints, correspond precisely to the beliefs of an agent who only knows α. Thus, a reconstruction of a major branch of nonmonotonicity happens entirely within a monotonic logic. Levesque also proposed an axiomatization that characterizes the semantics in the propositional case, which allows, among other things, formal proofs of its flavor of nonmonotonicity. In his axiom system, to better understand the relationship between O and K, he interprets {a mathematical formula}Oα to syntactically denote {a mathematical formula}Kα∧N¬α using a new modal operator N. Here, {a mathematical formula}N¬α is to be read as “at most α is known,” which can be contrasted with the usual {a mathematical formula}Kα that, in fact, could be read as “at least α is known” since {a mathematical formula}Kα does not preclude {a mathematical formula}K(α∧β) from holding, in general. With this new operator in hand, Levesque shows that by treating K and N to be fully introspective, the following axiom is all that is needed to completely characterize the semantics:{a mathematical formula}
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      This is clearly a novel axiom, and while it gives only knowing the intended properties, it also raises concerns when considering generalizations (as we shall shortly see). We remark that Levesque also proposed an axiomatic characterization for the first-order case, but this was shown to be incomplete by Halpern and Lakemeyer [9]. In fact, Halpern and Lakemeyer proved a stronger result: there cannot be a complete and recursive axiomatization.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Levesque's logic, however, only deals with a single agent. It seems perfectly natural to consider only knowing in the context of multiple agents. For example, imagine Alice having a secret p. It is reasonable to imagine that she believes the following:{a mathematical formula} If this sentence and p is all that Alice knows, then it should come out that Alice believes that Bob does not know her secret p. More generally, of course, one would often like to perspicuously characterize the beliefs of agents in multiagent settings, and here too, an account of only knowing would prove useful.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Motivated by such scenarios, a number of attempts have been made over the years to extend only knowing to the many agent case [10], [11], [12], [13], [14]. That is, in contrast to classical epistemic logic where multiagent extensions are immediate [1], generalizing only knowing has been shown to be very challenging [12]. In a sense, this is because an interesting technicality: the modality O has a subtle relationship to the classical operator K which makes extensions non-trivial. Moreover, proposing an accompanying axiomatization is also challenging: notice that the multiagent version of A5 cannot be restricted to propositional formulas, since this would preclude us from performing derivations with nestings of only knowing operators. Unfortunately, this leads to a circularity: we would like such an axiom to hold for any consistent (not necessarily objective) formula, but to deal with consistency we would need an axiom system.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      We discuss the aforementioned attempts in greater detail in the subsequent sections, but basically, we show that all of them have undesirable properties:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="•">
       Early propositional proposals by Lakemeyer [10] and Halpern [11] are shown to exhibit unintuitive features about only knowing. In fact, in later work, Halpern and Lakemeyer [12] argue why neither of these proposals satisfactorily capture only knowing.
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       To remedy some of the shortcomings of their proposals, Halpern and Lakemeyer [12] developed a revised account that does seem to successfully model multiagent only knowing. But it has proof-theoretic notions in the semantics. Precisely for this reason, that proposal is not natural. Most significantly, it is not clear how their ideas would generalize to the first-order case. That is, as we already noted above, there cannot be a complete first-order axiomatization of only-knowing even for a single agent. Hence we cannot even get off the ground envisaging a semantics that appeals to its own proof theory as in [12]. Finally, for generalizing A5, they define the semantic notion of validity directly in the language as a modal operator, which adds considerable complexity to the axiomatization for technical reasons only.
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       Lastly, an approach by Waaler [13] avoids such an axiomatization of validity, but by appealing to a sequent calculus formulation. To characterize the truth conditions for this axiom system, they provide a rather involved model-theoretic account formulated over Kripke structures that are required to satisfy a number of non-trivial constraints. Moreover, here too, only a propositional language is considered.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      It is worth noting that all these attempts appeal to arbitrary Kripke structures, and thus already deviate from Levesque's simple model theory that understands worlds as truth valuations.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In sum, despite the many attempts, it has remained an open question whether there is a natural semantics for only knowing in the multiagent setting for a first-order language. Provided such a semantics can be found, a second question is whether there is a proof theory for the propositional subset which avoids the complications introduced in [12]. The crucial item on the agenda, of course, is an appropriate generalization of A5. A third question is if this line of work would lead to a first-order multiagent generalization of AEL.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In this work, we answer in the affirmative for all three questions.{sup:2} We show that for a quantified language with equality, there is indeed a semantics for multiagent only knowing that extends Levesque's approach in a natural way. There is a caveat, however. The semantics is not defined for simultaneously satisfying an infinite set of sentences with unbounded nestings of modal operators, the implications of which are discussed later. But we are willing to give this up since in return, we get (for the first time) a very simple possible-world style account of multiagent only knowing. For the propositional subset, there is also a sound and complete axiomatization that faithfully generalizes Levesque's proof theory. Different from [12], we do not enrich the language any more than necessary (modal operators for each agent), and we do not make use of Kripke models. Interestingly, for the propositional subset, we establish a precise relationship with [12], and this shows that we avoid their problems in a reasonable manner. Finally, we obtain a first-order multiagent generalization of AEL, defined using notions of classical logical entailment, as an analogue to Levesque's result.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      We are organized as follows. We begin by reviewing Levesque's logic of only knowing.{sup:3} Following [12], we then emphasize some salient features of only knowing. Next, we define a semantics for multiagent only knowing with so-called k-structures, and discuss how the salient features are captured in our framework. We then turn to an axiomatization in the propositional case, which is treated in two steps: we first discuss an axiomatization for a restricted fragment of the language, developed by Lakemeyer [10], and then show how that should be extended for the full language. We demonstrate our axiomatization using examples exhibiting nonmonotonicity. Next, we establish a relationship to [12], before turning to a multiagent version of AEL. Finally, we discuss related work and conclude.
     </paragraph>
    </section>
    <section label="2">
     {a mathematical formula}OL: the logic of only knowing
     <paragraph>
      Levesque's logic {a mathematical formula}OL is a first-order modal dialect with equality and a countably infinite set of standard names, which are like constants syntactically but will also serve as the universe of discourse in the semantics.{sup:4} More precisely, the logical symbols of the language consist of the following sets:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="•">
       a countably infinite supply of (individual) variables, written as x, y, or z, possibly with subscripts or superscripts;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       a countably infinite supply of standard names, written schematically as n or m, possibly with subscripts or superscripts;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       the equality symbol, written =;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       modal operators K and N;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       the usual logical connectives {a mathematical formula}∀,∨,¬, parenthesis, and punctuation, such as comma and period.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      Other connectives like ∧, ⊃, ≡, and ∃ are taken for their usual syntactic abbreviations.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      The non-logical symbols of {a mathematical formula}OL consist of predicate symbols (of every arity), written schematically as P or Q, and intended to be domain specific properties and relations. To keep matters simple, function symbols are not considered in this language.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      We call a predicate other than =, applied to first-order variables or standard names, an atomic formula or atom. A ground atom is an atom whose arguments are standard names only. We write {a mathematical formula}αnx to mean that all occurrences of the free variable x are substituted in α by standard name n. A formula without free variables is called a sentence. A formula not mentioning any modalities is called objective. A formula is called subjective if every atom is in the scope of a modality.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      The semantics is defined wrt worlds, which are simply sets of ground atoms. The set of all possible worlds is denoted as {a mathematical formula}W. The standard names are thus rigid designators, and denote precisely the same entities in all worlds. An epistemic state e is any set of possible worlds over {a mathematical formula}W. A pair {a mathematical formula}(e,w), where w is a world and e an epistemic state, is called a model and the truth of sentences in {a mathematical formula}OL is defined as follows:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="1.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨p iff {a mathematical formula}p∈w for a ground atom p,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="2.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨(m=n) iff m and n are identical standard names,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="3.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨¬α iff {a mathematical formula}e,w⊭α,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="4.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨α∨β iff {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨α or {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨β,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="5.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨∀x.α iff {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨αnx for all standard names n,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="6.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨Kα iff for all {a mathematical formula}w′∈e, {a mathematical formula}e,w′⊨α,
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="7.">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨Nα iff for all {a mathematical formula}w′∉e, {a mathematical formula}e,w′⊨α.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      As mentioned earlier, we read {a mathematical formula}Kα as “at least α is believed.” Of course, this is the classical knowledge operator, and (at least) α is believed iff it is true at all worlds considered possible. We read {a mathematical formula}N¬α as “at most α is believed” since if the agent knows more than α, he would not consider all worlds where α holds epistemically possible. Thus, (at most) α is believed to be false iff it is true at all worlds considered impossible. Now we say that an agent only knows α, written {a mathematical formula}Oα, to mean:{a mathematical formula} where worlds in e are precisely those where α is true. That is,
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="•">
       {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨Oα iff for all {a mathematical formula}w′, {a mathematical formula}w′∈e iff {a mathematical formula}e,w′⊨α.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      Note that the only difference to the semantics for K is that an “if” becomes an “iff”.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Validity and satisfiability are defined as usual, that is, a formula α is valid (⊨α) iff for every set of worlds e and every {a mathematical formula}w∈W, {a mathematical formula}e,w⊨α.{sup:5}
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      It is not hard to show that {a mathematical formula}Oα⊃Kα is a valid sentence in {a mathematical formula}OL. Moreover, the operators K and N enjoy the usual properties of K45 modalities [1]. For example, both {a mathematical formula}Kα⊃KKα and {a mathematical formula}¬Nα⊃N¬Nα are valid sentences in {a mathematical formula}OL.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      As we mentioned earlier, for the propositional case the semantics can be understood in terms of the following proof theory:
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Axioms:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item>
       A1. All instances of propositional logic,
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       A2. {a mathematical formula}K(α⊃β)⊃(Kα⊃Kβ),
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       A3. {a mathematical formula}N(α⊃β)⊃(Nα⊃Nβ),
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       A4. {a mathematical formula}σ⊃Kσ∧Nσ for any subjective σ,
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       A5. {a mathematical formula}Nα⊃¬Kα if ¬α is a propositionally consistent objective formula.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      Inference Rules:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item>
       MP. From α and {a mathematical formula}α⊃β infer β.
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       NEC. From α infer {a mathematical formula}Kα and {a mathematical formula}Nα.{sup:6}
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      Essentially, axioms {a mathematical formula}A2–A4 tell us that K and N separately have all properties of a K45 modal operator. In addition, the axiom A4 tells us that K and N are mutually introspective, that is, {a mathematical formula}Kα⊃NKα is valid. Perhaps, the most interesting axiom is A5 which establishes the connection between K and N, and gives O the desired properties.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Let us now conclude our review of {a mathematical formula}OL by focusing on three properties of the semantics outlined by [12], which should provide guidance when considering extensions to {a mathematical formula}OL:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item>
       Evaluating formulas of the form {a mathematical formula}Nα does not affect an agent's possibilities, i.e. the epistemic state e remains fixed.
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       A union of the epistemically possible worlds in e, wrt which K is evaluated, and the impossible worlds, wrt which N is evaluated, is absolute and independent of e, and is the set of all conceivable worlds {a mathematical formula}W. The intuition is that the exact complement of an agent's possibilities is used in evaluating N.
      </list-item>
      <list-item>
       For every set of conceivable worlds, there is always a model where precisely this set is the epistemic state.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      A closer look informs us that P1 is essential for the soundness of A4 in Levesque's proof theory. Indeed, since this axiom makes {a mathematical formula}Kα⊃NKα valid, it follows that an epistemic state that interprets {a mathematical formula}Kα is also one where {a mathematical formula}NKα is true. P2 is essential for the soundness of A5 in Levesque's proof theory. This can be reasoned as follows. Suppose α is any non-valid formula and {a mathematical formula}Nα is satisfied in a model {a mathematical formula}(e,w). By axiom A5, {a mathematical formula}¬Kα is also true at {a mathematical formula}(e,w). That is, since α is true in all the impossible worlds, and since ¬α is satisfiable by assumption, there must be a possible world that satisfies ¬α. Therefore, α is not believed at {a mathematical formula}(e,w). Finally, P3 allows the possibility to only know any objective formula.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Interestingly, although these notions seem clear enough in the single agent case, generalizing them to the many agent case is non-trivial. Roughly speaking, the problem is that in the single agent case a possible state of affairs is simply captured by an objective formula, but that is no longer true in the multiagent case. When multiple agents are in the picture, a possibility, intuitively, should not only talk about what is true in the world but also about what others may believe. So p is just as objective in agent i's perspective as {a mathematical formula}Kjp (read: “j believes p”). Therefore, the appropriate generalization of possibility are i-objective formulas, by which we mean formulas such as p and {a mathematical formula}Kjp (defined formally below). We return to analyze the faithfulness of our approach wrt these properties after introducing a semantics in the next section.{sup:7}
     </paragraph>
    </section>
    <section label="3">
     <section-title>
      Multiagent only knowing
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      We begin by extending the language. Let {a mathematical formula}OLn be a first-order modal language that enriches the non-modal subset of {a mathematical formula}OL with modal operators {a mathematical formula}Ki and {a mathematical formula}Ni for each agent i. For ease of exposition, we only consider two agents A (Alice) and B (Bob), that is, let {a mathematical formula}i∈{A,B}. Extensions to more agents are straightforward. By analogy to the single agent case, we freely use {a mathematical formula}Oi, such that {a mathematical formula}Oiα abbreviates {a mathematical formula}Kiα∧Ni¬α, and is read as “all that i knows is α.” The terms objective and subjective are now understood relative to an agent i. A formula is called i-objective if all epistemic operators which do not occur within the scope of another epistemic operator are of the form {a mathematical formula}Mj for {a mathematical formula}i≠j, where M denotes K or N. A formula is called i-subjective if every atom is in the scope of an epistemic operator and all epistemic operators which do not occur within the scope of another epistemic operator are of the form {a mathematical formula}Mi. Intuitively, i-subjective formulas refer to what is true about i's beliefs about the world whereas i-objective formulas refer to what is true about the world from i's perspective, which may include beliefs about what other agents believe. We will continue to call a formula objective if it does not contain any modal operators. A formula is basic if it does not mention any {a mathematical formula}Ni for {a mathematical formula}i∈{A,B}.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In the following it will be useful to refer to the degree of nestings of modal operators within a formula, where we lump together consecutive nestings of operators for the same agent.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph label="Definition 1">
      The i-depth of a formula α, denoted {a mathematical formula}|α|i, is defined inductively as:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="1.">
       {a mathematical formula}|α|i=1 for atoms;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="2.">
       {a mathematical formula}|¬α|i=|α|i;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="3.">
       {a mathematical formula}|∀x.α|i=|α|i;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="4.">
       {a mathematical formula}|α∨β|i=max⁡(|α|i,|β|i);
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="5.">
       {a mathematical formula}|Miα|i=|α|i;
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="6.">
       {a mathematical formula}|Mjα|i=|α|j+1, for {a mathematical formula}j≠i.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph label="Example 2">
      To illustrate the notion of depth, consider the formula {a mathematical formula}KAKBKAp∨KBq:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item label="•">
       {a mathematical formula}|KAKBKAp∨KBq|A=max(|KAKBKAp|A,|KBq|A)=3 because
      </list-item>
      <list-item label="•">
       {a mathematical formula}|KAKBKAp∨KBq|B=max(|KAKBKAp|B,|KBq|B)=4 because
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
      When a formula has a maximal A-depth of k and a maximal B-depth of j, we say that the formula has maximal{a mathematical formula}A,B-depth of{a mathematical formula}k,j for brevity.
     </paragraph>
     <section label="3.1">
      <section-title>
       A semantics
      </section-title>
      <paragraph>
       The purpose of a semantics is to interpret i-subjective and i-objective formulas. Knowledge in multiagent systems is traditionally modeled by means of a generalization of Kripke structures to n agents [1]; Fig. 1 depicts a simple structure of this sort. However, such structures do not share the simplicity of Levesque's semantical framework that treats worlds as truth valuations.{sup:8} Most significantly, as mentioned earlier, there do not seem to be natural ways to capture all the necessary features of multiagent only knowing in a first-order setting with such structures [9], [12].
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Our approach will be based on a simple notion called k-structures, where the idea is to keep separate the worlds A believes from the worlds she considers B to believe, and so on, to k levels.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Formally, let the set of all possible worlds {a mathematical formula}W be defined exactly as before. Then:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Definition 3">
       Given {a mathematical formula}k≥0, we define {a mathematical formula}Ek inductively:
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="•">
        {a mathematical formula}E0={{}};
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="•">
        {a mathematical formula}Ek=2W×Ek−1.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       Intuitively, a k-structure determines knowledge of depth k. For example, {a mathematical formula}e0 is an epistemic state where everything is (vacuously) believed. On the other hand, a (nonempty) {a mathematical formula}e1 is of the form {a mathematical formula}{(w,{}),(w′,{})} which describes an agent whose beliefs about the world are determined by w and {a mathematical formula}w′. However, such an agent is fully ignorant of what the other agent believes, and so has nothing interesting to say about the other agent. Analogously, a (nonempty) {a mathematical formula}e2 is a set of the form {a mathematical formula}{(w,e1),(w′,e′1),…} which states that at w an agent, say A, believes B to consider worlds from {a mathematical formula}e1 possible, and at {a mathematical formula}w′ she believes B to consider worlds from {a mathematical formula}e′1 possible; Fig. 2 depicts such an epistemic state for A. This captures the intuition that A has partial information about B, and so her beliefs about B differ at different worlds. In the sequel, we often drop the index and simply use e, when it is clear from the context.{sup:9}
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       When modeling a k-structure, say {a mathematical formula}ek, for A we denote it as {a mathematical formula}eAk. Analogously, when modeling a j-structure, say {a mathematical formula}ej, for B we denote it as {a mathematical formula}eBj. We define a k-structure {a mathematical formula}ek for A, a j-structure {a mathematical formula}ej for B and a world w as a {a mathematical formula}(k,j)-model{a mathematical formula}(eAk,eBj,w). The semantic rules are as follows:
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="1.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨p iff {a mathematical formula}p∈w, where p is a ground atom;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="2.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨(n=m) iff n and m are the same names;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="3.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨¬α iff {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊭α;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="4.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨α∨β iff {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨α or {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨β;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="5.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨∀x. α iff {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨αnx for all names n;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="6.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨KAα iff for all {a mathematical formula}(w′,e)∈eAk, {a mathematical formula}eAk,e,w′⊨α;
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="7.">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨NAα iff for all {a mathematical formula}w′, for all {a mathematical formula}e∈Ek−1, if {a mathematical formula}(w′,e)∉eAk then {a mathematical formula}eAk,e,w′⊨α.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       Since {a mathematical formula}OAα is syntactically understood as {a mathematical formula}KAα∧NA¬α, it follows that
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="•">
        {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨OAα iff for all {a mathematical formula}w′, for all {a mathematical formula}e∈Ek−1, {a mathematical formula}(w′,e)∈eAk iff {a mathematical formula}eAk,e,w′⊨α.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       The semantic rules for formulas of the form {a mathematical formula}KBα, {a mathematical formula}NBα and hence, {a mathematical formula}OBα, are given analogously.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       A formula α is said to be satisfiable iff there is a triple {a mathematical formula}(eAk,eBj,w) for some k and j, such that {a mathematical formula}eAk,eBj,w⊨α. The formula is said to be valid iff it is true at all {a mathematical formula}(k,j)-models, for all k and j.{sup:10}
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Given a {a mathematical formula}(k,j)-model{a mathematical formula}(eAk,eBj,w), we often write {a mathematical formula}{},eBj,w⊨α when α is A-objective because the k-structure for A is irrelevant. Analogously, for B-objective formulas, we often write {a mathematical formula}eAk,{},w⊨α. When the formula α is objective, we omit the structures for A and B altogether and simply write {a mathematical formula}w⊨α.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
