     <section label="3.3">
      Generalizing the features of {a mathematical formula}OL
      <paragraph>
       In this section, we intend to demonstrate that our semantics for {a mathematical formula}OLn generalizes the features of {a mathematical formula}OL, namely {a mathematical formula}P1–P3, in a suitable manner.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       We begin by briefly summarizing the substantiation by earlier proposals. Lakemeyer [10] and Halpern [11] independently attempted to extend {a mathematical formula}OL to the many agent case. Both approaches provide a semantics by means of multiagent Kripke structures.{sup:12} There are some subtle differences in these proposals, but the main restriction is that they only allow a propositional language.{sup:13} Besides that, the model theory for these proposals has problems. For example, Lakemeyer's approach is based on a {a mathematical formula}K45ncanonical model, which is a Kripke structure whose worlds are all maximally consistent (wrt the axioms of the modal logic {a mathematical formula}K45n) subsets of basic formulas (cf.Definition 20). Canonical models are often criticized for being overly proof-theoretic since truth is based on the notion of consistency. So the approach is not “natural” in the usual sense where a semantics independently justifies truth in a logic. That notwithstanding, [12] further show that the analogue of P3 does not hold in the Lakemeyer proposal. Similarly, in the proposal by Halpern, the analogue of P2 does not hold. Consequently, these approaches show some peculiar properties, which we will look at shortly. Ergo, apart from their propositional restriction, they do not truly generalize {a mathematical formula}OL's properties. Henceforth, following [12], we will refer to the Lakemeyer proposal as the canonical model approach, and to the Halpern proposal as the i-set approach. (While the details of Halpern's proposal need not concern us here, it is based on the idea of constructing models where epistemic states correspond to sets of maximal i-objective formulas, or i-sets for short.)
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       We will now show that in the first-order case, the analogues of all three properties hold in our proposal. The first item on the agenda is clarifying the notion of an epistemic possibility. As discussed earlier, the appropriate generalization of a possibility in the many agent case is a set of i-objective formulas. The question, then, is which set of i-objective formulas represent the epistemic possibilities of the agent? To answer that, we define the following:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Definition 12">
       Suppose {a mathematical formula}M=(eAk,eBj,w) is a {a mathematical formula}(k,j)-model. We define {a mathematical formula}obji(M) as follows:
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item label="1.">
        {a mathematical formula}objA(M)={A-objective ϕ of B-depth≤j|M⊨ϕ};
       </list-item>
       <list-item label="2.">
        {a mathematical formula}objB(M)={B-objective ϕ of A-depth≤k|M⊨ϕ}.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       To see the intuition behind the definition, suppose that we are interested in the set of A-objective formulas true at the model M. Clearly, the objective formulas true at w are to be included in this set, as are the B-subjective formulas that hold wrt the j-structure {a mathematical formula}eBj in M. Note that these formulas do not actually capture A's possibilities, which are, in fact, determined strictly by the k-structure {a mathematical formula}eAk. Hence, we define {a mathematical formula}ObjA(eAk) as the set of all A-objectives formulas that A considers possible, which is obtained from the set of all k-structures {a mathematical formula}(w,e)∈eAk. With this elaborated, let us look at the generalizations of {a mathematical formula}P1–P3:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Generalizing P1:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       When a single agent is involved, this property ensures that epistemic possibilities are not affected when evaluating N. To see why this idea holds for {a mathematical formula}OLn in a straightforward manner, consider any model {a mathematical formula}M=(eAk,eBj,w). Then, A's possibilities are given as {a mathematical formula}ObjA(eAk). Now, to evaluate formulas of the form {a mathematical formula}NAα, we are interested in the set of models{a mathematical formula} Observe that A's possibilities in every {a mathematical formula}M′∈M are still given by {a mathematical formula}ObjA(eAk). Therefore, epistemic possibilities are not affected on evaluating {a mathematical formula}Ni.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Generalizing P2:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Here we are concerned with the property that the evaluation of {a mathematical formula}Kiα and {a mathematical formula}Niα is wrt the set of all possibilities. Moreover, the set of all possibilities is independent of the epistemic state.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       To demonstrate this property, let α be any A-objective formula, say of maximal B-depth k, which represents a possibility in A's view. Then let {a mathematical formula}eAk+1 be any epistemic state satisfying {a mathematical formula}KAα. By analogy to the single agent case, the set of models used to interpret {a mathematical formula}NAα must be the exact complement of {a mathematical formula}eAk+1, in the sense that these models together with {a mathematical formula}eAk+1 is the full set of conceivable states. Now since epistemic notions are defined wrt the depth of formulas, the set of conceivable states of depth {a mathematical formula}k+1 is {a mathematical formula}Ek+1. It is then easy to show that wrt {a mathematical formula}Ek+1, structures considered for the interpretation of {a mathematical formula}KAα and {a mathematical formula}NAα are truly complements of each other. Moreover, {a mathematical formula}Ek+1 is independent of {a mathematical formula}eAk+1.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 13">
       Let α be A-objective of B-depth k. Then, the set of{a mathematical formula}(k+1)-structures that evaluate{a mathematical formula}KAαand{a mathematical formula}NAαis{a mathematical formula}Ek+1. (Analogously stated for B.)
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proof">
       The proof is a rather direct one by the definition of the semantics. □
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Generalizing P3:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       The third property, by analogy to the single agent case, must allow us to characterize epistemic states from any set of i-objective formulas. Intuitively, given such a set of formulas, we must have a model where precisely this set represents the beliefs of an epistemic state.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       A proof-theoretic strategy to proving this property consists of showing that there is an epistemic state corresponding to every set of maximally consistent sets of formulas [12]. This arises from the observation that every set of formulas can be extended to a maximally consistent set of formulas, and so the strategy proves P3. However, this is fraught with difficulty in a first-order setting. We have, for one, no clear understanding of what the axiom system should look like in the first-order case even for a single agent [9].
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       The alternative is to consider a purely semantic notion of a complete description of a possibility, analogous to the proof-theoretically characterized notion of a maximally consistent set of formulas. That is, we consider the equivalent notion of a maximally satisfiable set of formulas. More precisely, let Σ be a satisfiable set of A-objective (not necessarily basic) formulas, of maximal B-depth k. Let γ be any A-objective formula such that {a mathematical formula}|γ|B≤k. If {a mathematical formula}Σ∪{γ} is satisfiable, then let {a mathematical formula}Σ1=Σ∪{γ}. Otherwise, let {a mathematical formula}Σ1=Σ. By considering all A-objective formulas of maximal B-depth k, construct {a mathematical formula}Σ2,… , iteratively and let {a mathematical formula}Σ⁎ be the limit. We term a set of formulas constructed in this fashion as an A-set of B-depth k. (There may be many A-sets corresponding to Σ depending on our choice of γ and the subsequent formulas added.)
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       We now show that given any set of i-sets of a certain depth, there is a model where precisely this set characterizes the epistemic state.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Theorem 14">
       Let σ be a satisfiable objective formula,{a mathematical formula}SAany set of A-sets of B-depth k, and{a mathematical formula}SBany set of B-sets of A-depth j. Then there is a model{a mathematical formula}M⁎=(e⁎Ak+1,e⁎Bj+1,w⁎)such that{a mathematical formula}M⁎⊨σ,{a mathematical formula}SA=ObjA(e⁎Ak+1)and{a mathematical formula}SB=ObjB(e⁎Bj+1).
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proof">
       Consider {a mathematical formula}SA. Each {a mathematical formula}S′∈SA is a maximally satisfiable set of A-objective formulas and thus by construction, there is a {a mathematical formula}(k+1)-structure {a mathematical formula}(w′,eBk) such that {a mathematical formula}{},eBk,w′⊨S′. Let{a mathematical formula} It is immediate to verify that {a mathematical formula}ObjA(e⁎Ak+1)=SA. In an analogous fashion construct {a mathematical formula}e⁎Bj+1 from {a mathematical formula}SB. Finally by assumption σ is satisfiable in some world, say {a mathematical formula}w⁎. □
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       To summarize, generalized variants of Levesque's properties are satisfied in the semantical framework. To add further support to this claim, we now present the unintuitive properties exhibited by the canonical model and the i-set approaches. Meanwhile, we show that our approach does not suffer from these problems.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Lakemeyer [10] noted that certain types of epistemic states cannot be constructed in his approach. This is a consequence of the approach not satisfying P3. More precisely,
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 15">
       (See[10].) For any proposition p and{a mathematical formula}i≠j,{a mathematical formula}¬Oi¬Ojpis valid in the canonical model approach.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       {a mathematical formula}OA¬OBp says that all that Alice knows is that Bob does not only know p. Lakemeyer [10] admits that the validity of {a mathematical formula}¬OA¬OBp is unintuitive because after all, Bob could honestly tell Alice that he does not only know p. The main reason for this peculiarity, it turns out, is that by proposing a semantics based on {a mathematical formula}K45n canonical models, agents only entertain basic i-objective possibilities. In contrast, we show that {a mathematical formula}¬Oi¬Ojp is not valid in our approach. This is a consequence of Theorem 14 that shows that P3 holds.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 16">
       For any proposition p and{a mathematical formula}i≠j,{a mathematical formula}Oi¬Ojpis satisfiable (in a model of appropriate depth).
