    <section label="4">
     <section-title>
      Proof theory
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      Naturally, the next question is if there are axioms that characterize the semantics in the propositional case. We show that the answer is affirmative. However, obtaining such an axiomatization is not entirely straightforward. Let us begin by recalling Levesque's proof theory from Section 2, and taking notice, in particular, of the following axiom:
     </paragraph>
     <list>
      <list-item>
       A5. {a mathematical formula}Nα⊃¬Kα if ¬α is a propositionally consistent objective formula.
      </list-item>
     </list>
     <paragraph>
