     <section label="4.2">
      {a mathematical formula}AXn is not complete for {a mathematical formula}OLn
      <paragraph>
       The soundness of {a mathematical formula}AXn in Theorem 25 is easily lifted for all formulas {a mathematical formula}α∈OLn. The only interesting case is the {a mathematical formula}A5n schema. But because the application of the schema is restricted to basic formulas, the argument given holds immediately also for {a mathematical formula}OLn. To show that {a mathematical formula}AXn is not a complete axiomatization, we simply need to find a formula in {a mathematical formula}OLn such that it is valid but not provable using {a mathematical formula}AXn.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 31">
       {a mathematical formula}⊨Ki(¬TRUE)⊃¬Ni¬Oj¬Oip.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       However, it is not possible to prove this formula using {a mathematical formula}AXn[12, see Theorem 4.7]. Therefore {a mathematical formula}AXn is not complete for formulas in {a mathematical formula}OLn. The validity of the non-provable formula {a mathematical formula}¬Oi¬Ojp∈OLn wrt the canonical model approach demonstrates in a similar spirit that {a mathematical formula}AXn is also not a complete axiomatization in that approach.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Part of the problem is {a mathematical formula}A5n. It has to somehow go beyond basic formulas. But this is a problem of circularity. On the one hand, we would need {a mathematical formula}Niα⊃¬Kiα to hold for any consistent i-objective α. On the other, to deal with consistency we have to clarify and define an axiom system.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       The approach taken by Halpern and Lakemeyer [12] is to introduce the semantic notion of validity, and the dual notion of satisfiability, into the language as modal operators. The motivation is that, by syntactically representing satisfiability, the notion of consistency can be inductively defined from propositional formulas to modal ones. Not surprisingly, a new set of axioms is needed to characterize this feature, by way of which the axiomatization is significantly different from Levesque's formulation for the single agent case. We give the details in the next section but for now let us refer to their axiomatic proposal as {a mathematical formula}AXn′.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Halpern and Lakemeyer show that the axioms {a mathematical formula}AXn′ characterize an infinite model, very much in the spirit of the canonical model from Definition 20. There are differences to Definition 20, however. First, the worlds are defined as maximally consistent {a mathematical formula}AXn′-consistent formulas. Second, {a mathematical formula}Ki and {a mathematical formula}Ni are treated as separate modal operators, which results in two separate accessibility relations. Owing to this difference, the model is referred to as the extended canonical model.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       One approach towards an axiomatization for our semantics is to perhaps show that valid formulas wrt our approach coincides with the extended canonical model. But having to axiomatize validity does not seem natural. One of the principal reasons for axiomatic formulations is to have an insightful view on valid formulas in a logic, independent of semantic notions. Further, the proof theory is difficult to use. Lastly, we would still understand the axioms to characterize a semantics bridged on proof-theoretic elements.
      </paragraph>
     </section>
