     <section label="4.5">
      <section-title>
       Axiomatizing validity
      </section-title>
      <paragraph>
       We already discussed that both [10] and [11] fail to capture the intuitions of multiagent only knowing. Besides, Lakemeyer's proof theory is restricted to formulas in {a mathematical formula}OLn−. Extending this work, Halpern and Lakemeyer [12] proposed a multiagent only knowing logic that does handle the nesting of {a mathematical formula}Ni operators. However, as discussed, there are two undesirable features. The first is a semantics based on canonical models, and the second is a proof theory that axiomatizes validity. Although such a construction is far from natural, we now show that they do indeed capture the desired properties of only knowing. More precisely, we show that this proposal and our framework agree on provable formulas in {a mathematical formula}OLn. This mainly instructs us that our axiomatization avoids such problems in a reasonable manner.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       We begin by presenting the essential formal features of their approach. More precisely, this involves enriching {a mathematical formula}OLn with a new modal operator V, for validity. We read {a mathematical formula}Vα as “α is valid”. A modal operator S, for satisfiability, is freely used such that {a mathematical formula}S(α) syntactically denotes {a mathematical formula}¬V(¬α). Let {a mathematical formula}OLn+ be the addition of V to {a mathematical formula}OLn.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       To handle the circularity of consistency, Halpern and Lakemeyer propose an axiom system, which we will denote as {a mathematical formula}AXn′, that has the following set of schemas:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Axioms:
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item>
        {a mathematical formula}A1n–A4n,
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        {a mathematical formula}A5n′. {a mathematical formula}S(¬α)⊃(Niα⊃¬Kiα) if α is i-objective,
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        V1. {a mathematical formula}V(α)∧V(α⊃β)⊃V(β),
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        V2. {a mathematical formula}S(α) if α is a satisfiable propositional formula,
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        <list>
         <list-item>
          V3. {a mathematical formula}⋀S(α∧βz)∧⋀S(γ∧δz′)∧V(α∨γ)⊃
         </list-item>
        </list>
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        V4. {a mathematical formula}S(α)∧S(β)⊃S(α∧β) if α is i-objective and β is i-subjective.
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       Inference Rules:
      </paragraph>
      <list>
       <list-item>
        MP and NEC,
       </list-item>
       <list-item>
        {a mathematical formula}NECV. From α infer {a mathematical formula}V(α).
       </list-item>
      </list>
      <paragraph>
       The axioms may seem somewhat mysterious but intuitively, they allow us to extend the notion of consistency from propositional formulas to modal ones. To see this, consider the axiom V2 which allows us to include satisfiable propositional formulas in the scope of S. V3 then allows us to construct consistent i-subjective formulas from i-objective ones. Note also that the generalized A5 in this proof theory is {a mathematical formula}A5n′. This then allows us to invoke the {a mathematical formula}Nivs. {a mathematical formula}Ki relationship on all falsifiable i-objective formulas, that is, the formulas α for which {a mathematical formula}S(¬α) is provable from the given premises. The axiom V1 and the inference rule {a mathematical formula}NECV make the modality V a normal modal operator[16].
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       We mentioned in Section 4.2 that {a mathematical formula}AXn′ characterizes the extended canonical model. We do not present the details of this structure here since we will not directly make use of it.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       In order to enable comparisons with the {a mathematical formula}AXn′ approach, it seems obvious that we need to extend our logic to handle the enriched language {a mathematical formula}OLn+.{sup:17} However, it turns out that there is a much simpler alternative, which rests on the following result proved by Halpern and Lakemeyer:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Theorem 41">
       (See[12].) Every formula{a mathematical formula}α∈OLn+is provably equivalent (wrt{a mathematical formula}AXn′) to some formula{a mathematical formula}α′∈OLn.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       The theorem essentially tells us that as far as we are concerned regarding derivations of {a mathematical formula}AXn′, it suffices to restrict our attention to the language {a mathematical formula}OLn. Now, to obtain a correspondence between the two axiom systems, we first demonstrate that {a mathematical formula}S(α), where {a mathematical formula}α∈OLnt, is provable by {a mathematical formula}AXn′ iff α is consistent wrt {a mathematical formula}AXnt. This will then allow us to use Theorem 41 to establish the agreement on provable formulas.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 42">
       Let σ be any propositional formula, ζ any A-subjective formula and ξ any B-subjective formula. Then{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(σ∧ζ∧ξ)iff{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(σ),{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(ζ)and{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(ξ).
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proof">
       If {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(σ), {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(ζ) and {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(ξ), we can use V4 to get {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(σ∧ζ) because σ is A-objective and ζ is A-subjective. We can then use V4 again to get {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(σ∧ζ∧ξ), because ξ is B-subjective and {a mathematical formula}σ∧ζ is B-objective.For the other direction, since {a mathematical formula}AXn′ characterizes Kripke structures [12, Corollary 5.4], and because S corresponds to satisfiability, it follows that if {a mathematical formula}σ∧ζ∧ξ is satisfiable then {a mathematical formula}σ,ζ and ξ must be individually satisfiable. □
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proposition 43">
       (See[12, Proposition 5.1].) For any{a mathematical formula}α1,…,αl,{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(⋁αu)≡⋁S(αu).
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Theorem 44">
