      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       This allows us to obtain the main result of the section:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Theorem 45">
       For all{a mathematical formula}α∈OLnt,{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢αiff{a mathematical formula}AXnt⊢α.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Proof">
       Suppose {a mathematical formula}AXnt⊢α and {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊬α. We prove by contradiction. Proposition 5.1 in [12] states that if α is not provable from {a mathematical formula}AXn′, then {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢¬V(α), i.e.{a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢S(¬α). But by assumption, ¬α is not consistent wrt {a mathematical formula}AXnt. Then {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊬S(¬α) because of Theorem 44. This is a contradiction.Conversely, suppose {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢α. Then by {a mathematical formula}NECV, it follows that {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢V(α), and so {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢¬S(¬α). Thus, {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊬S(¬α). Thus, ¬α is not consistent wrt {a mathematical formula}AXnt by Theorem 44. Therefore, {a mathematical formula}AXnt⊢α. □
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Recall the main message of Theorem 41: it is sufficient to restrict ourselves to formulas from {a mathematical formula}OLn with regards to the Halpern and Lakemeyer approach. Therefore, Theorem 45 establishes an exact correspondence between the Halpern and Lakemeyer approach and our approach, without any of their problems.
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
       Halpern and Lakemeyer also prove that deciding if {a mathematical formula}AXn′⊢α is PSPACE-complete [12, Theorem 5.6]. And so, as an immediate corollary, we inherit this complexity analysis:
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph label="Corollary 46">
