    <section label="6">
     <section-title>
      Related work
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      In this work, we were concerned with the logic of only knowing, and its generalization to a multiagent case. There are two major strands of work, the first on formal models of knowledge with notions similar to only knowing, and the second on multiagent flavors of nonmonotonicity, and we discuss both below.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      First, let us begin by considering logics of knowledge and belief. This is a fundamental area of research; although instigated by philosophers, it has since found applications in computer science, game theory and artificial intelligence [1]. The question as to which axioms for knowledge are appropriate has been a cause for discussion [17], but K45 and S5 are perhaps the most used in knowledge representation. Multiagent logics of knowledge have also received considerable attention [18]. Here, extensions to logics like {a mathematical formula}K45n for reasoning about time, actions, desires, and intentions, among others, are being investigated.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      The extension pursued in this work, of course, is with regards to obtaining a precise characterization for the beliefs of an agent. This was achieved by means of appealing to Levesque's notion of only knowing which, roughly speaking, augments classical epistemic logic with the modality O. However, there are a number of related notions, including, for example, minimal knowledge[2], [19], and total knowledge[20]. The notion of minimal knowledge from [2] is very similar in spirit to (propositional) {a mathematical formula}OL, especially when the two proposals are restricted to objective knowledge bases. But “all I know” is only a meta-language concept and not part of the vocabulary in the minimal knowledge proposal. Moreover, somewhat surprisingly, it turns out that reasoning about minimal knowledge is harder than reasoning about only knowing: see [21] for a complexity analysis (in the propositional setting wrt a single agent). Analogously, total knowledge is similar to {a mathematical formula}OL, except that knowledge is required to be true. Interestingly, for objective sentences, only knowing and total knowledge seem to coincide, but in general, the connection between {a mathematical formula}OL and AEL has no parallel with total knowledge. Some AEL defaults, it turns out, lead to an inconsistency [3]. We refer interested readers to [3], [12], [21] for more on {a mathematical formula}OL and related approaches. Among these, minimal knowledge has been extended to deal with multiple agents [2], [19], and only knowing, of course, has been extended to reason about multiple agents [10], [11], [12], [13], [14], discussed throughout this work.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Over the years, {a mathematical formula}OL has been extended in various ways, including a dynamic extension [7], probabilistic extensions [22], [23], among others [24]. More recently, only knowing has been shown to capture Reiter's default logic [25], [26], as well as other nonmonotonic formalisms [27], which has the same benefit that nonmonotonicity can be now inspected in terms of a simple (monotonic) semantics. We remark there are also other variants of only knowing, inspired by {a mathematical formula}OL, such as a model by Ben-David and Gafni [28], but these have problems that are discussed in [29].
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Regarding AEL, besides the work already cited, a few other papers look at multiagent autoepistemic reasoning. In [30], [31], multiagent extensions of stable sets and stable expansions are proposed, together with special inference rules that allow for nonmonotonic inferences, which sometimes seem unwarranted on intuitive grounds. Moreover, the underlying language does not permit quantifying-in. Like Moore's original formulation, that proposal is also not motivated by a semantical account. In the context of speech acts, multiagent nonmonotonicity is investigated in [32], [33]. Typically, these correspond to situations where there are two agents: a speaker and a listener. Nonmonotonicity arises due to certain prototypical assumptions such as the assumption that a sentence with particular features relates to a particular property regarding the speaker. For instance, the utterance of a false fact by a speaker indicates that the speaker is not sincere. However, general purpose nonmonotonic reasoning is not considered in these proposals.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In terms of our proof-theoretic investigations of only knowing in the propositional case, we followed the approaches of [4], [12], [34] by considering Hilbert-style axiom systems. For us, the main purpose of a sound and complete axiom system is to provide another concise characterization of the valid sentences of the logic. If one is interested in actual proof systems, then other approaches such as tableaux or Gentzen-style systems (as in [13]) may be more appropriate. In the single-agent case, Bonatti and Olivetti [35] developed sequent calculi for nonmonotonic logics, which recently led to insights into the proof complexity [36] of nonmonotonic reasoning. It would be interesting to see whether and how these concepts can be generalized to multi-agent settings.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      As a final remark, we observe that the intuition of k-structures seems closely related to the proposal of knowledge structures[29]. Although restricted to a propositional language, and although only knowing is not considered, this proposal also constructs epistemic states at various depths. (See [37] for a similar semantical notion in game theory.) For an agent, a 1-world is simply a set of truth assignments to primitive propositions. This roughly corresponds to a set of worlds, similar to a 1-structure. However, a 2-world considers the triple: truth assignment to primitive propositions, a 1-world for A, and a 1-world for B. So this differs from our proposal slightly. They also expect k-worlds to satisfy various constraints, including one about knowledge always being correct. Despite these differences, they are also motivated by the ease of capturing non-beliefs, and so we believe a closer examination of the two proposals might be useful.
     </paragraph>
    </section>
    <section label="7">
     <section-title>
      Conclusion and outlook
     </section-title>
     <paragraph>
      In this work, we are concerned with only knowing, and how that extends to the multiagent case. Only knowing rationally reconstructs nonmonotonicity, AEL's flavor in particular, in a monotonic modal logic. Besides providing a clean model theory for a first-order language, the notion of only knowing is a very intuitive concept, allowing for a succinct and natural formulation for the beliefs and non-beliefs of an agent. An extension to the many agent case, then, seems pertinent.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In stark contrast to Levesque's simple logic, however, previous treatments of multiagent only knowing are surprisingly complex with undesirable features. They are also propositional. In this work, we looked at a first-order proposal. In order to do so, we had to deviate from the usual Kripke-based semantics, and appeal to a depth-of-KB based account. But as far as entailments are concerned, we showed that for finite KBs, such as in practical applications, sentences about what is believed and not believed at any depth can be reasoned with. We then argued that this proposal maintains our intuitions about {a mathematical formula}OL.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      For the propositional case, the logic can be characterized also in terms of a proof theory, which goes beyond the language restrictions of the axiomatization from [10]. In contrast to the work of [12], our proof theory does not bring concepts from the semantics to the axiomatization. Using the proof theory we gave example derivations exhibiting multiagent nonmonotonic reasoning. Interestingly, the axiomatization corresponds to the work of [12] but without having to resort to their complications.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Finally, as an extension to Levesque's insight that only knowing captures AEL, we considered a multiagent generalization of AEL and showed that a similar relationship holds with our framework.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      In general, {a mathematical formula}OL can also be thought as a formal foundation for a knowledge representation service, where we query the KB on what the agent knows and does not know [3]. For this, a fundamental result called the representation theorem[38] shows how reasoning about knowledge can be reduced to first-order reasoning. We believe a similar move is possible with {a mathematical formula}OLn, and we would like to investigate this in the future. For preliminary results on a representation theorem for {a mathematical formula}OLn, see [39].
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      A second major direction for future work is extending the semantics to handle unbounded modalities, as required, for example, with the notion of common knowledge. Perhaps an approach similar to the knowledge structures proposal [29] would prove fruitful. As discussed above, they too have epistemic states of various depths, and so a model of their language has epistemic states of every depth, including infinitary ones, allowing them to define a semantics for common knowledge. Following such an account, an analysis of the computational complexity for deciding the validity of formulas in the propositional case would also be insightful.
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      On a different front, as pointed out in [40], when imagining knowledge-based agents in dynamical worlds, non-beliefs play an important role in informing the agent about what it is ignorant about. The agent then may be persuaded to deliberate on ways to complete its knowledge, say by sensing[41]. This intuition has encouraged extensions of {a mathematical formula}OL towards the design of practical cognitive agents [40], [42], [43], by introducing the appropriate variants of K and O in the language of the situation calculus [41], [44], [45]. Then, by stipulating all that is known initially, only knowing exhibits the desired behavior for how beliefs should change as a result of physical and sensing actions. Recently, this only knowing variant of the situation calculus has also been extended to capture defaults over actions [46], and reasoning about noisy effectors [22], [47]. In similar spirit, work on an amalgamation of actions and {a mathematical formula}OLn is under way [48]. Here too, only knowing offers a simple system to reason about the beliefs and the defaults of agents, especially in the context of how knowledge and ignorance changes as agents perceive and act in complex dynamical domains. From a practical standpoint, in dynamical systems, we would need to reason about knowledge and actions. Fortunately, there are well-known methodologies for resolving actions, either by reducing queries about the future to queries about the initial state or by updating the knowledge base [7], [41], [46], [49]. This would then mean that we would only need to reason about knowledge. Here is perhaps a second use of a representation theorem: it would provide the computational means for realizing such first-order reasoners. To see this in action, we refer interested readers to [39].
     </paragraph>
     <paragraph>
      Epistemic logics play an important role in the investigations on multiagent interactions in knowledge representation applications, and we think the above line of work contributes to the area, especially in providing a formal specification for knowledge-based reasoners operating in an incompletely known world.
     </paragraph>
